      "message": "+ethan, to double-check my idea about code transformation, and the difficulty thereof.\n\nSo, this is conflating a couple things:\n1) The signature and calling convention of main() in .fp files\n2) The convention of each GrFragmentProcessor\u0027s emitted code\n3) The signature of runtime SkSL, which is currently passed through (somewhat) in GrSkSLFP, but doesn\u0027t need to be.\n\nI\u0027d rather focus on #1 first, and do it in a way that we don\u0027t need the redundant assignment in the .fp files. (Aside: I\u0027m not actually sure what\u0027s happening here - we\u0027re feeding code to the SkSL compiler from the final GrFragmentProcessor emitCode functions that\u0027s now full of return statements - how is that working, if we haven\u0027t changed the signature of the enclosing function? Ah, I guess processor functions *do* always return half4, right? So do we have back-to-back return statements now? The new ones you added, plus the ones generated by writeProcessorFunction? And this only works because of https://skia-review.googlesource.com/c/skia/+/285105, which ensures that ALL processor functions are in helper sub-functions. Starting to make sense...). Anyway, I think that changing #2 so that the FP itself is responsible for returning the color is a separate issue, and is tied into a larger piece of how we feed the shaders for a network of FPs to the compiler. Can we hold off on that, for now?\n\nFor #1, what I\u0027d like to see is just the .fp signature/convention switched over, with some massaging in the compiler to transform the generated code to adapt to whatever convention the GrFPs might need. There is some logic already in SkSL::IRGenerator::convertFunction to deal with main in different contexts (kPipelineStage \u003d\u003d runtime effect, kFragmentProcessor \u003d .fp file). Interestingly, we validate the number and type of parameters, but we don\u0027t look at the return type. Oops. That function also does some tricks to map the incoming parameters to builtin variables, so that the passed-in parameters bind to the input color, input coords, etc... Can we do something similar so that .fp files can just have a return, and we can make sure that (returned) value ends up in the right place in the SkSL produced by the generated CPP code? (This probably requires a more clever transformation, or an enclosing function?)",
